commText: And with that win, CSK would be fairly confident of making the cut for the first qualifier now. It might take something extraordinary from LSG to topple them now, but let's see what Krunal Pandya and co. have to offer. Over to the Eden Gardens now, bye from here...

B0$ It was a must win game, and my 50th game for this franchise. Feels good to make a contribution. I think the wicket was holding up, was difficult to hit pacers but with spinners we thought we had a chance with short straight boundaries. We set the platform and after 10-12 overs and then we thought with Shivam, Mahi bhai and Jaddu to come in, we could really attack. (On Devon Conway) He had 1-2 areas where he wanted to improve, and he's improved a lot. Playing at home in Chennai can be tough, but he's adjusted very well. He's a guy who's always open to conversation, I love having him around even off the field.

formatValue: Ruturaj Gaikwad | Player of the Match:

commText: B0$ There is no recipe for success, you try and pick the best players and give them the best slot to perform. And groom them in the areas where they are not strong, somebody has to sacrifice their slot for the team. Credit to the management as well, they always back us. But, the players are most important, without the players we can't do anything. I think death bowling, confidence is very important. Tushar has developed because he is able to execute under pressure, he has the confidence now. And when you keep playing the same players, it helps. I think the bowlers have also taken the responsibility, Pathirana is quite a natural to bowling at the death but Deshpande has really developed there. I think we need to figure out and pick players who are team first - not bothered about individual performance and perform the best at knockout stages. It is difficult to judge from the outside, we tryand adjust to the players and environment as well. Even if they come 10%, we can adjust 50% to fit them better into the team.

B0$ It was an important match, got the result we wanted. We wanted to win with a big margin. I think it was a 160 wicket, getting 220 was a tremendous job as our openers did very well. We had a long partnership which set the base for us, 220 for more than enough for us. I find this pitch better, in Chennai you sweat a lot and that makes it difficult to bowl slower balls. I have been practicing that because if you don’t get a new ball you need to have something different to your skill set. I think Tushar has improved a lot, he’s getting the confidence in his stock ball. If you don't believe in that, you switch to plan B and plan C too early. This same mistake I did earlier. Pathirana is very difficult to face, we have a great combination with him bowling at the death.

B0$Credit to CSK, they outbatted us today. We did see that it was a good pitch, boundaries early in the over and we could have put more pressure on their bowlers. There were some positives, we didn't go too badly with the ball, with the bat we didn't get partnerships, lost wickets in clumps, we lost some games badly and that hurt, we'll have to look at these things and come back strongly next season. We can't keep blaming the wickets, we have been getting some of these this season. We have to adapt to the conditions however tough it might be. You have to back your game plan, hit boundaries and use your feet against spin. You can't get bogged down against any bowlers, partnerships would have been handy. I want to be consistent at the top of the order, you need to have a good SR to give yourself a chance, but we kept losing too many wickets in the batting powerplay, these are some of the things we need to think about.

B0$ A game that was decided as soon as Ruturaj and Conway got going in the first innings powerplay. Delhi Capials were always chasing the game, first to try and break the opening partnership, then to try and keep Jadeja and Dube quiet. In the chase, they lost Prithvi Shaw cheaply and then Deepak Chahar got two in two balls as Salt and Rossouw were dismissed early. David Warner held fort from one end, and struck a few neat blows against the CSK spinners. But he didn't get enough support as Axar, Yash Dhull, Aman Khan all got starts and then fell off. In the end, Warner also fell victim to a Pathirana slower delivery. All boxes ticked for CSK in this thumping win, as Theekshana got back amongst the wickets as well by picking two in the final over.

commText: B0$ After that sort of a start from Rutu and Conway, CSK were always getting an above-par total. The question was how high will it be? B0$: A big double-header weekend starting today and the final four league matches of this season's Indian Premier League has a lot riding on it. Only Gujarat Titans have a confirmed place in the playoffs and they'll finish as the table toppers, regardless of what happens over the next couple of days. The first match features the Super Kings up against the Delhi Capitals with the former looking to lock in a playoff berth. A win will do them just that and they'll then hope for Lucknow to lose tonight's game to ensure a top-2 finish, giving them two shots at reaching the final. On the other hand, the Capitals have nothing to lose and would like to end their campaign with a win at home. The pressure then will be squarely on MS Dhoni's men.

B0$ by B1$  
  
If Chennai Super Kings aren't forever in "Que Sera Sera" mode, they are surely there now. "Whatever will be, will be," Michael Hussey announced rather poetically ahead of their last league game against Delhi Capitals, on Friday.  
  
Despite being placed second on the points table, their playoff qualification chances hinge on the result of their last league game. A win secures them the berth, and a loss would leave their fate hanging on the events elsewhere in the competition (they will need one of LSG, MI or RCB to lose). That's not the only concern - there's also a top-two finish at stake.  
  
There is complex mathematics at play, and Hussey feels simplification is the best way out of this muddle, the cliched - give it your best shot and ignore the rest.  
  
After all, their opposition aren't carrying that baggage anymore. Delhi Capitals, the first to exit the competition, are taking motivation from getting a chance to spoil the party for the rest, Shane Watson admitted. Without the pressure to win, they brought down Punjab Kings quite emphatically and would be keen to end a disappointing home run with a victory.  
  
However, Watson isn't sure if they can replicate the success of the previous game at their home venue, where they have won only two out of six matches. The pitches at home haven't suited the squad they have assembled, he believes. But whose home ground will it be anyway? For all of DC's branding of 'Neela Pehen Ke Aana (Come wearing blue)" inside the stadium, the hawkers were selling yellow jerseys on the streets a day before the game.  
  
But can the team that wilted under pressure rattle the calmness of CSK on the big day?
